segments.text: probably transit authority people, suggested that they assumed that this transit line, if you will, if it goes in the West Park corridor, really wouldn't disrupt much of anything else.
And my problem was that... Did you try to convince them of this?
Urge them?
It seems to me that if you're putting in... Now, it runs...
It's right here.
From West University out to Alif?
Well, they leave.
It runs back over here somewhere.
But anyway, it runs out that way.
It picks up Greenway and everything else.
But what I...
They just... We had a lot of arguments about what the effects would be.
And they're only looking at transportation issues.
And I say, hold on.
We have certain things we're going to be blamed for.
Traffic congestion, inefficient sewer, inefficient water, solid waste.
How are we going to deal with the development that occurs due to your putting in virtually in another mode another freeway?
And where you've got those transit stations, you're going to have some activity because property value in there is going to go sky high, and you're going to have some intensive development.
And...
I think that they're going to be looking at that, but I'm not sure.
And I'm a little concerned about that because we'll get blamed for it.
You can't get to the goddamn station because there's not enough street.
Well, you know.
Rick, there are two excellent models that exist in the world for this sort of opportunity.
One is in Toronto, and the other is in Stockholm.
The mass transit planning in both cases
has been done hand in hand with land use planning.
And the land use planning proceeds in total sync with the mass transit planning, the underground, the subway systems, or the tunnel bond out of Stockholm and so forth.
And they would not think of planning high density unless they knew they had a transit stop there.
I understand that Toronto in the last 20 years has made a fantastic turnaround from being a nowhere city of North America to possibly the showcase of how to do it today.
So maybe your people ought to make a couple field trips.
Yeah.
Yeah, I went to Germany.
I don't know.
That was a trip I missed.
But I'm looking at it now.
The other point that we did discuss briefly that I'd like to talk about is the absence, it seems, in planning of a generalist planner.
And you find that everyone is diving off into a specialty, be it health systems or transportation or whatever.
And it seems like the role of the generalist planner, which
at least used to be what planners were, that they knew a process and therefore could apply it to anything.
I think that we've been outrun by our legal people.
I find that most planning decisions and policy decisions that are made in a number of cities, including this one, that are planning decisions, are being made by lawyers.
And...
I'm not sure that that's something that was in the long term good for cities.
And you can adjudicate anything.
But there are other issues involved that a more general type planning person could probably see a little more of.
That's why I work with the lawyer that I work with, and he and I
And I deal policy.
He deals legal.
But it's a shame.
I have not met very many.
I'm a transportation planner.
I'm a health planner.
I've never said shit.
Well, you remember in comprehensive planning, you talked about the concept of the hyphenated planner.
Yes.
You'd have the transportation hyphen planner, the health hyphen planner, the whatever hyphen planner.
But who are the planner planners?
That's the question you're asking.
Where have they gone?
Are we training any today in the universities?
What is your perception of the recent grads from the Texas planning schools?
Well, most of them are specialists, and that's fine.
I've not been very impressed with them.
I have interviewed a number of people,
They're very intense about what they're doing, but they're very myopic about what they're doing.
It reminds me of engineers a little bit.
You know, you give somebody a situation and then they'll say, well, what they need is this service.
They may not need that service, but that's what they were taught to do.
A health plan.
Well, they need dental care.
Low-income people need dental care.
Low-income people need money.
They don't need dental care.
Fuck the dental care.
Go get the money as it is.
That's the kind of thing.
I think people don't cut through the bullshit.

I think we've become isolated unto ourselves with our own little vocabulary at a time when you've got to explain to people that a council person who may be a developer or maybe something doesn't understand
the kinds of things that the planners talk about.
And I think you pick up vocabularies.
I speak HUD, a little EPA, and a little EDA.
But they're very different dialects.
And I think we need to get the whole planning profession in general needs to get down a little bit.
And be political.
And know what you're doing.
Be able to explain.
And know in your head and in your heart, you know, what you're doing.
And be able to explain these things to people.
Don't sit back and make recommendations because somebody said so.
You know, but I would much rather see a more general plan or come out of some of these things.
Because I feel all of us were.
I don't think anybody had any special drinking beer, you know.
But I think most of the people that I know are doing quite well.
And we might get into a specialty.
We might not.
There have been three or four of us that have gotten straight into management positions.
And nobody ever thought about being a city manager.
Far be it for me to think about being an executive assistant to the mayor of Houston.
Or like, found out, didn't know.
City manager.
Right.
Crabtree's assistant city manager.
There are several others, which I can't think of right now.
Well, Dana Bennett, sure.
Right, Dana Bennett.
You know, but you're not going to have a unimodal transportation planner going anywhere except on the staff of that operation.
And they're just other things to be considered.
And I think a good comprehensive, not comprehensive, I never use that word, a general planning base where you learn the planning process and then go on
if you want an area of specialization seems to me to be the route to go.
Otherwise, you know, other than slugs on somebody's staff, the goddamn lawyers are going to run it.
You're saying it's dangerous to tie an educational program into current federal mandated funded projects.
Absolutely.
Because, I mean, look, the transportation bills weren't funded.
You know, all of a sudden, 701 went away.
And then 208.
208 screwed up.
So everybody's gearing to these federal programs rather than taking an overall view.
Because you can learn the vocabulary.
I mean, it doesn't take you very long.
Well, this all gets back to the role of higher education in the professions.
Rick, thanks very much for your time and your careful consideration to
these questions involving the planning process as we have come to know it in Houston.
And I want to thank you for the Texas chapter of the American Planning Association and for the Texas A&M University Department of Regional Planning.
And we look forward to seeing you visit us in the near future.
Thank you.
